PowerShares DB Gold Fund Getting Very Oversold






ETFChannel.com




Jul 7, 2017 10:50 AM EDT













 
















































 In trading on Friday, shares of the PowerShares DB Gold Fund ETF ( DGL) entered into oversold territory, changing hands as low as $38.71 per share. We define oversold territory using the Relative Strength Index, or RSI, which is a technical analysis indicator used to measure momentum on a scale of zero to 100. A stock is considered to be oversold if the RSI reading falls below 30.   In the case of PowerShares DB Gold Fund, the RSI reading has hit 29.5 — by comparison, the RSI reading for the S&P 500 is currently 49.6.  START SLIDESHOW:Find out what 9 other oversold stocks you need to know about »  A bullish investor could look at DGL's 29.5 reading as a sign that the recent heavy selling is in the process of exhausting itself, and begin to look for entry point opportunities on the buy side.  Looking at a chart of one year performance (below), DGL's low point in its 52 week range is $36.22 per share, with $44.84 as the 52 week high point — that compares with a last trade of $38.79. PowerShares DB Gold Fund shares are currently trading off about 0.9% on the day.   



 



 










































